Bottom front of the bbl is equipped with the 1889-style ramrod bayonet attachment that has straight edge and wrap-around locking ears. Bayonet is a rnd steel rod with knurled section at the end with dimpled tip.  Bayonet case is complete and in tact. Including US medallion. According to Flayderman’s Guide to Antique American Firearms there were only 1,000 of these rare rifles produced. Referenced publication states “The production run was made for trial use and distribution was wide spread. Survival rate is quite small. Very scarce.”. According to The .45-70 Springfield Book II 1865-1893, Frasca, there were actually 1,013 of these rifles produced, 504 in 1885 and 509 in 1886 with respectively dated cartouches. Very few of these rare rifles are known today in orig configuration. According to the Frasca book, after the trials, most of the rifles were dismantled and serviceable parts were salvaged. CONDITION: Very good. Steel parts retain a dark attic patina with some blue showing through and moderate pitting over the top exposed surfaces. Stock has a few nicks & scratches, otherwise is sound and retains a cleaned oiled finish. Mechanics are fine, brilliant shiny bore. No Sling (3,000-5,000)

postcontent: ** NEW IN BOX**Ruger® designed the M77® Hawkeye® Bolt-Action Rifle with 2 principles in mind: simplicity and strength. At the core of the M77 Hawkeye is an ultra-reliable action based on the Mauser 98—considered one of the strongest and most dependable firearm designs for over 100 years. The M77 Hawkeye action utilizes a controlled feed mechanism with a large claw extractor that takes a solid hold on the cartridge's rim as it is being fed into the chamber. The controlled round feeding, plus a sturdy fixed blade ejector and a 1-piece stainless steel bolt make the M77 Hawkeye a top choice for serious big game hunting anywhere in the world. Integral scope mounts are machined directly on the steel receiver to accept Ruger scope rings (included), eliminating any chance of screwed-on bases coming loose in the field. A steel trigger guard protects the trigger in the case of a fall, and a hinged, all-steel floorplate allows hunters to unload the rifle safely without cycling cartridges through the chamber. The floorplate latch fits flush with the trigger guard to avoid accidently dumping cartridges at an inconvenient moment. The Ruger M77 Hawkeye features the LC6™ trigger that comes from the factory smooth and crisp with an optimized pull weight for hunting. A 3-position safety allows the shooter to load or unload the rifle with the safety engaged in the middle position. In the rearward position, the bolt is locked where it is extremely unlikely to get bumped or knock off safe, making it an ideal safety for hunters who have to navigate rugged terrain. The safety is rapidly accessible with the either the shooter's thumb or forefinger, and can also be grasped between the thumb and forefinger and moved stealthily to the fire position when game is close. The Ruger M77 Hawkeye Bolt-Action Rifle comes with an ergonomic, finely contoured, walnut stock with cut checkering and an elegant oiled finish. A rubber butt pad softens felt recoil and keeps the butt-stock from slipping on the shooter's shoulder. Sling swivel studs provide for the quick attachment of a hunting sling. The Ruger M77 Hawkeye is a rugged, reliable hunting rifle that will give generations of hard use. title: For Sale/Trade:  SOLD - Bayard Model 1908 7.65 mm, .32 ACP circa 1918 - Matching numbers! - Rare
postcontent: Model:....................... Bayard Model 1908 7.65mmSN:............................. 1892XXManufacturer:....... Bayard PieperCaliber:..................... .32 ACP (7.65mm)Origin:....................... BelgiumYear made:.............. maybe 1914-1918Materials:................. Blued steel with black gripsBarrel length:........... 2.23 in.Capacity:................... 5 shotsTrigger pull:.............. 8.5 lbsWeight unloaded:.. 16.2 oz / 460 gCondition:................. 85%Extras:......................... Soft caseAll matching part numbers. Magazine is marked “7.65mm”. The grips may be horn based on faded color.Note: A collector pointed out that the proofmarks are Prussian and the gun may actually date to the German occupation of Belgium during WWI 1914-1918. German Imperial Eagle proofmarks on right side of frame and slide. No Belgian Liege proofs.  Made during German occupation of Belgian factory. The serial number is in the 100,000 - 200,000 range of Prussian German pistols.This nearly 100 year old pistol was the smallest .32 ACP (and .380 ACP) until the advent of the Keltec composite polymer/aluminum frame concealed carry guns in the early 1990s.Manufactured by Anciens Etablissements Pieper, Herstal, Belgium, the Bayard Model 1908 was introduced in .32 ACP in 1910, .380 caliber in 1911 and .25 ACP in 1912. All three calibers are hammer-fired straight-blow back pistols of identical design and similar size, except for the barrel, breech and magazines. All are referred to as the Model 1908.Like many other guns introduced in the first decade of the 20th century, the Bayard 1908 follows the Browning FN 1900 design (the first commercially successful semi-auto handgun) with the barrel positioned below the recoil spring mechanism. However, the 1908 also added some elements from the Browning 1903 hammer fired design. While Browning (FN & Colt) had moved on to simpler, more elegant and reliable designs that were less labor intensive to produce, Anciens Etablissements Pieper continued to manufacture the Bayard 1908 well into the 1930s.The Model 1908 has a unique take down mechanism. The removable front sight retains the recoil spring. Disassembly is accomplished by pushing backwards on the front sight, then rotating it up and back to remove the sight and recoil spring. The slide can the be pulled to the rear and upwards, off the receiver.Sixty years after the introduction of the Bayard 1908, Smith & Wesson resurrected this design with the S&W Model 61. The .22LR S&W Model 61 emulated many aspects of the Browning 1900 & Bayard 1908 designs, notably the recoil spring above the barrel and the front sight take down mechanism. The S&W Model 61 was less successful than the Bayard 1908 and was only produced for 4 years from 1970-1973.Pre-owned, used, vintage, curio and relic, and antique firearms or other weapons are sold as-is with no warranty, expressed or implied.The ammo, quarter and keys to the Corvette are only for scale and not included in the sale.I’m selling this pistol and other parts of my collection to pay for some recent rifle and reloading purchases.Requires FFL transfer to ship.
